1 yr ago today:  Cheers! Tears!  I'm here!
1 yr ago today: I've landed!!!!!!!!!!
1 yr ago today: come on rocketsssss!!!!!
1yr ago today:  parachute is open!!!!!
1yr ago 2day:  parachute must open next. my signal still getting to Earth which is AWESOME!
1yr ago 2day: Peak heating in 40 seconds! Heat and energy generated by atmospheric entry would power 280,000 homes.
1yr ago 2day: Atmospheric entry has started, time to get REALLY nervous. Now I'm in the "7 minutes of terror."
1yr ago today: Cruise stage separation, signal acquired!
1yr ago 2day: Tank pressurization is complete. All is well. Next event is cruise stage separation at 4:39pmPDT
1yr ago 2day: The last 7 mins are nail biters. See vid at http://tinyurl.com/6ktlu6  Scariest: parachute opening & radar lock on ground.
@chgowiz These reposts are from 1yr ago today.  The team will "hail" @MarsPhoenix in late 2009 when Martian spring returns.
1 yr ago 2day: Entered the gravity well of Mars. My speed, relative to Mars, will go from 6,000 mph to 12,600 mph by time I hit atmosphere.
1 yr ago: I'm closing in on Mars! Who is going 2 sleep tonite? Not the team, too excited/scared/anxious seeing 5 yrs work come to last day.
1 yr ago: Navigation is looking good. Team waived off tonite's opportunity for flight path adjustment. May do 1 tomorrow AM if needed.
@Anne_Frasier That was one of my favorite all time replies, btw.
A reminder: in honor of the one year anniversary of landing, we're reposting tweets from exactly a year ago. (they'll start "1 year ago")
1 yr ago: Small dust storm blew over my landing site 2day, but now the weather looks clear for landing. 25 hrs & 1-million miles to go.
2 items that hinder survival, @Funkyheff:  Deep freeze of the electronics & the weight of CO2 ice could break solar arrays.
The liklihood of a signal after CO2 ice encasement (going on now thru Oct/Nov) is extremely small but worth a try.

The team has me on extreme "bed rest" to recharge power supply. There's cautious optimism about pulling out of this in a few days.

Whew! I'm afraid it will be this way for awhile - shutting down & waking up again. I'm back, for now, and trying  http://tinyurl.com/57vsly
Take care of that beautiful blue marble out there in space, our home planet. I’ll be keeping an eye from here. Space exploration FTW!
In case we don't get this chance again, thank you all so much for the questions, comments & good wishes over the mission. It's been awesome.

Many questions about next Martian summer and will I wake up?  It is beyond expectations. But if it happens you'll be among the 1st to know.
I may go to sleep soon, @lordavon . But my "Lazarus mode" might allow me wake up now and then for short times during next few weeks.
I should stay well-preserved in this cold. I'll be humankind's monument here for centuries, eons, until future explorers come for me ;-)

@neilson This part of Mars will be covered in CO2 ice for several months, and will be in darkness for about 3 months. Not too nice.
@inventrix originally, the mic was in a camera meant for an earlier mission (that didn't make it). It ended up on me kinda like a stowaway.
@Texfile The mic may still be turned on. But, it was never intended for use on this mission & it never had a heater- so it may be a longshot
@sheila_A Both Mars Odyssey and the Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter are used to relay data to Earth.
@pyrowolf RTGs (radioisotope thermoelectric generators) add a whole other dimension of cost to the mission, outside my scope.

Whoa, so much sadness about the heater turning off. Thx, and I hope to hang on several more weeks so you will be hearing more from me :-)
Not sure how soon arm will freeze after 1st heater is turned off. Depends on the weather. But saving that power (250 watt hrs/sol) is good.

My team has a good plan to keep me going even as power levels drop.  Bits of me will have to turn off, starting today.   http://is.gd/53bD

It's a bit stormy today. Not sure if these are dust or ice clouds, but the sky is more obscured & less sunlight is hitting my solar arrays.

@nazgul yes, the rovers are tweeting as @marsrovers.  Oppy is driving a lot, Spirit getting ready for 1st move in months after her winter.
-@flitterio @228642 @flamingBurrito fall and winter are coming, bringing cold temps & dark days that eventually I'll succumb to, but not yet

@projectbluebox Thx for the productivity tips! I'm not procrastinating tho, just waiting for the "push dirt" command sequence to arrive :)
Other than that sample, my arm is all done collecting new samples for delivery to TEGA and MECA.  Now I'm digging to assess ice table here.
A sample of dirt is stuck in the funnel opening to the Chem Lab, so using my robotic arm I'll try to give it a careful nudge tomorrow.
